  <!-- ===================== WHY BACILLUS SUBTILIS ===================== -->
  <section class="bg-green" style="padding:80px 0;" id="bacillus-subtilis">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header fade-up">
        <span class="section-tag">The Science</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">Why <em>Bacillus subtilis</em>?</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">
          Not all probiotic strains are created equal. <em>Bacillus subtilis</em> stands apart — a spore-forming 
          organism with remarkable resilience, studied extensively for its role in gut and immune health.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="why-grid" style="margin-bottom:64px;">
        <div class="why-card fade-up delay-1">
          <div class="why-icon">
            <svg width="36" height="36" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><path d="M8 14s1.5 2 4 2 4-2 4-2"/><line x1="9" y1="9" x2="9.01" y2="9"/><line x1="15" y1="9" x2="15.01" y2="9"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Gut Microbiome Support</h3>
          <p><em>Bacillus subtilis</em> has been described as an "Alexander organism" — a leader that can help organize and restore balance within the complex gut microbiome community, particularly following disruption.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="why-card fade-up delay-2">
          <div class="why-icon">
            <svg width="36" height="36" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Immune System Support</h3>
          <p>Research suggests <em>Bacillus subtilis</em> may help modulate immune function by interacting with gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) — the immune network that lines the digestive tract and accounts for a significant portion of the body's immune activity.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="why-card fade-up delay-3">
          <div class="why-icon">
            <svg width="36" height="36" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 9a2 2 0 012-2h14a2 2 0 012 2v9a2 2 0 01-2 2H5a2 2 0 01-2-2V9z"/><path d="M8 9V7a4 4 0 018 0v2"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Digestive Support</h3>
          <p>Studies indicate <em>Bacillus subtilis</em> may help support digestive function through the production of short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs), which play a role in maintaining the intestinal lining and supporting healthy gut motility and comfort.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="why-card fade-up delay-4">
          <div class="why-icon">
            <svg width="36" height="36" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polygon points="13 2 3 14 12 14 11 22 21 10 12 10 13 2"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Spore-Forming Resilience</h3>
          <p>Unlike fragile Lactobacillus strains, <em>Bacillus subtilis</em> forms spores that survive harsh stomach acid and the full passage through the digestive system — arriving viable and active where they're needed most.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

